04407nam a22006495i 9780292753754DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212013txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927537547 a10.7560/7456742doi  a(DE-B1597)586983  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aF1435.3.C75bB87 2013eb 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a305.800972812231 aBurrell, Jennifer L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMaya after War :bConflict, Power, and Politics in Guatemala /cJennifer L. Burrell. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (235 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. War and La Violencia in Todos Santos: Accounting for the Past -- t2. Localities in Conflict: Spaces and the Politics of Mapmaking -- t3. Histories and Silences -- t4. Reimagining Fiesta: Migration, Culture and Neoliberalism -- t5. After Lynching -- t6. Life and Death of a Rural Marero: Generations in Conflict -- tEpilogue: Waiting after War -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGuatemala’s thirty-six-year civil war culminated in peace accords in 1996, but the postwar transition has been marked by continued violence, including lynchings and the rise of gangs, as well as massive wage-labor exodus to the United States. For the Mam Maya municipality of Todos Santos Cuchumatán, inhabited by a predominantly indigenous peasant population, the aftermath of war and genocide resonates with a long-standing tension between state techniques of governance and ancient community-level power structures that incorporated concepts of kinship, gender, and generation. Showing the ways in which these complex histories are interlinked with wartime and enduring family/class conflicts, Maya after War provides a nuanced account of a unique transitional postwar situation, including the complex influence of neoliberal intervention. Drawing on ethnographic field research over a twenty-year period, Jennifer L. Burrell explores the after-war period in a locale where community struggles span culture, identity, and history. Investigating a range of tensions from the local to the international, Burrell employs unique methodologies, including mapmaking, history workshops, and an informal translation of a historic ethnography, to analyze the role of conflict in animating what matters to Todosanteros in their everyday lives and how the residents negotiate power. Examining the community-based divisions alongside national postwar contexts, Maya after War considers the aura of hope that surrounded the signing of the peace accords, and the subsequent doubt and waiting that have fueled unrest, encompassing generational conflicts. This study is a rich analysis of the multifaceted forces at work in the quest for peace, in Guatemala and beyond.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aEthnic conflictzGuatemala. 0aMayasxCrimes againstzGuatemala. 0aMayasxViolence againstzGuatemala. 0aSocial conflictzGuatemala. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/74567440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292753754423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292753754/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK